1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,608


2
00:00:00,608 --> 00:00:01,650
INSTRUCTOR: Good morning.

3
00:00:01,650 --> 00:00:05,370
I'm Dr. Georgios Antonios
Margonis, and in this lecture,

4
00:00:05,370 --> 00:00:07,890
I'll explain how
artificial intelligence--

5
00:00:07,890 --> 00:00:12,060
specifically
Interpretable AI, or IAI--

6
00:00:12,060 --> 00:00:16,100
can help us achieve
precision medicine.

7
00:00:16,100 --> 00:00:19,410
Let's begin with the overview
figure on this slide.

8
00:00:19,410 --> 00:00:24,150
It summarizes the key concepts
and steps we will cover today,

9
00:00:24,150 --> 00:00:26,750
and it introduces
the terms I will

10
00:00:26,750 --> 00:00:30,050
be using throughout the talk.

11
00:00:30,050 --> 00:00:31,820
We begin with the
two main sources

12
00:00:31,820 --> 00:00:36,590
of medical data, Randomized
Controlled Trials, or RCTs,

13
00:00:36,590 --> 00:00:41,210
and Real-World Data or RWD.

14
00:00:41,210 --> 00:00:44,240
RCT data come from
prospective studies

15
00:00:44,240 --> 00:00:47,300
designed to compare treatments.

16
00:00:47,300 --> 00:00:51,150
These studies are rigorous and
provide high-quality evidence,

17
00:00:51,150 --> 00:00:54,390
but they are also
expensive, time-consuming,

18
00:00:54,390 --> 00:00:58,520
and often limited by
ethical considerations.

19
00:00:58,520 --> 00:01:03,080
As a result, RCT data
are relatively scarce.

20
00:01:03,080 --> 00:01:06,620
In contrast, real-world
data, the byproducts

21
00:01:06,620 --> 00:01:10,970
of routine clinical care,
are abundant and inexpensive.

22
00:01:10,970 --> 00:01:13,810
But that abundance
comes with a price--

23
00:01:13,810 --> 00:01:15,820
bias.

24
00:01:15,820 --> 00:01:21,190
RWD are often affected by
various forms of bias that can

25
00:01:21,190 --> 00:01:24,430
distort treatment comparisons.

26
00:01:24,430 --> 00:01:26,350
So what are these biases?

27
00:01:26,350 --> 00:01:31,040
There are several-- immortal
time bias, selection bias,

28
00:01:31,040 --> 00:01:35,800
and, most problematic,
confounding by indication.

29
00:01:35,800 --> 00:01:38,590
Immortal time bias
and selection bias

30
00:01:38,590 --> 00:01:41,380
can typically be addressed
with appropriate study

31
00:01:41,380 --> 00:01:44,650
design and analytic methods.

32
00:01:44,650 --> 00:01:49,370
However, confounding, especially
unobserved confounding,

33
00:01:49,370 --> 00:01:53,470
is much harder to control
for and often cannot be fully

34
00:01:53,470 --> 00:01:56,830
addressed with current methods.

35
00:01:56,830 --> 00:01:59,890
To illustrate confounding,
look at the Kaplan-Meier plot

36
00:01:59,890 --> 00:02:01,810
on the slide.

37
00:02:01,810 --> 00:02:07,570
It shows patients with resected
GIST, a gastrointestinal tumor.

38
00:02:07,570 --> 00:02:10,330
The blue curve
represents those who

39
00:02:10,330 --> 00:02:15,890
received adjuvant imatinib, the
red curve those who did not.

40
00:02:15,890 --> 00:02:18,890
Paradoxically, the
group receiving imatinib

41
00:02:18,890 --> 00:02:20,840
appears to do worse.

42
00:02:20,840 --> 00:02:24,800
But we know from RCTs that
imatinib is effective.

43
00:02:24,800 --> 00:02:27,560
This is confounding at work.

44
00:02:27,560 --> 00:02:29,810
Patients who received
imatinib likely

45
00:02:29,810 --> 00:02:31,710
had more aggressive disease--

46
00:02:31,710 --> 00:02:34,490
for example, high
mitotic counts.

47
00:02:34,490 --> 00:02:36,960
This made clinicians
prescribe treatment,

48
00:02:36,960 --> 00:02:41,120
but it also independently
predicted poor outcomes.

49
00:02:41,120 --> 00:02:44,720
And this is the essence of a
confounder, a variable that

50
00:02:44,720 --> 00:02:50,390
influences both treatment
assignment and patient outcome.

51
00:02:50,390 --> 00:02:54,330
When the confounder is
recorded, such as mitotic count,

52
00:02:54,330 --> 00:02:57,800
you can adjust for it with
matching or regression.

53
00:02:57,800 --> 00:03:02,040
But when confounders are
unmeasured, or even unknown,

54
00:03:02,040 --> 00:03:05,450
the analysis becomes risky.

55
00:03:05,450 --> 00:03:07,260
RCTs solve this problem.

56
00:03:07,260 --> 00:03:12,020
Randomization balances both
known and unknown confounders

57
00:03:12,020 --> 00:03:15,230
across treatment arms.

58
00:03:15,230 --> 00:03:17,990
That means any
differences in outcomes

59
00:03:17,990 --> 00:03:22,130
can be attributed
directly to the treatment.

60
00:03:22,130 --> 00:03:24,720
In this lecture, I will
walk you through how

61
00:03:24,720 --> 00:03:28,500
we can use AI and optimization
methods to address

62
00:03:28,500 --> 00:03:33,900
both observed and unobserved
confounding in RWD, making

63
00:03:33,900 --> 00:03:37,860
it possible to generate
causal treatment insights even

64
00:03:37,860 --> 00:03:41,310
outside of trials.

65
00:03:41,310 --> 00:03:43,230
Once bias is accounted for--

66
00:03:43,230 --> 00:03:45,490
or absent, in the case of RCTs--

67
00:03:45,490 --> 00:03:49,710
we can turn to our goal,
precision medicine.

68
00:03:49,710 --> 00:03:52,620
According to the National
Cancer Institute,

69
00:03:52,620 --> 00:03:55,830
oncologic precision
medicine is the use

70
00:03:55,830 --> 00:03:58,800
of specific information
about a person's tumor

71
00:03:58,800 --> 00:04:01,440
to help plan treatment.

72
00:04:01,440 --> 00:04:06,210
Put simply, we want to move
from what works best on average

73
00:04:06,210 --> 00:04:11,070
to what works best for
this individual patient.

74
00:04:11,070 --> 00:04:15,750
But even when we have data
from RCTs, or the biased RWD,

75
00:04:15,750 --> 00:04:19,110
we don't always achieve
precision medicine.

76
00:04:19,110 --> 00:04:22,120
RCTs tell us what
works on average,

77
00:04:22,120 --> 00:04:27,060
but the average effect can
hide important variation.

78
00:04:27,060 --> 00:04:29,890
To move toward
patient-specific treatment,

79
00:04:29,890 --> 00:04:32,270
we need to uncover subgroups--

80
00:04:32,270 --> 00:04:36,290
patients who benefit, patients
who don't, and patients who

81
00:04:36,290 --> 00:04:39,260
may not need treatment at all.

82
00:04:39,260 --> 00:04:44,480
That's where
interpretable AI comes in.

83
00:04:44,480 --> 00:04:47,100
Using methods like
optimal policy trees,

84
00:04:47,100 --> 00:04:49,730
we can define
treatment-relevant subgroups

85
00:04:49,730 --> 00:04:53,960
in both RCT and RWD settings.

86
00:04:53,960 --> 00:04:56,430
These trees do not
output probabilities.

87
00:04:56,430 --> 00:05:00,200
They output clear,
rule-based groupings

88
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:03,770
based on clinical features.

89
00:05:03,770 --> 00:05:07,290
This makes the results
interpretable, inspectable,

90
00:05:07,290 --> 00:05:11,300
and testable, allowing us to
assess whether the identified

91
00:05:11,300 --> 00:05:15,230
subgroups are
clinically meaningful.

92
00:05:15,230 --> 00:05:17,540
This brings us to
the final goal,

93
00:05:17,540 --> 00:05:19,620
illustrated in the pie chart.

94
00:05:19,620 --> 00:05:22,490
We aim to first
identify patients

95
00:05:22,490 --> 00:05:26,390
who do not need treatment,
those with good prognoses

96
00:05:26,390 --> 00:05:28,880
who do well regardless.

97
00:05:28,880 --> 00:05:32,040
Then, among those who
do need treatment,

98
00:05:32,040 --> 00:05:35,870
we distinguish between those
who will actually benefit

99
00:05:35,870 --> 00:05:39,930
and those who will not because
not all high-risk patients

100
00:05:39,930 --> 00:05:42,510
respond.

101
00:05:42,510 --> 00:05:47,370
Now let's look at how this
lecture is structured.

102
00:05:47,370 --> 00:05:51,600
It will be divided
into three parts.

103
00:05:51,600 --> 00:05:56,970
First, I will discuss how to
use real-world data to identify

104
00:05:56,970 --> 00:05:59,560
patients who do not
need treatment--

105
00:05:59,560 --> 00:06:03,840
those with good prognoses
who do well regardless.

106
00:06:03,840 --> 00:06:09,660
Second, I will describe how to
use real-world data to identify,

107
00:06:09,660 --> 00:06:12,660
among those who do need
treatment, who will actually

108
00:06:12,660 --> 00:06:16,680
benefit and who will not because
not all high-risk patients

109
00:06:16,680 --> 00:06:18,330
respond.

110
00:06:18,330 --> 00:06:21,510
And, finally, in part
3, I will explain

111
00:06:21,510 --> 00:06:25,440
how to use IAI on
randomized trial data

112
00:06:25,440 --> 00:06:27,270
to identify patients
who actually

113
00:06:27,270 --> 00:06:31,230
benefit from a treatment.

114
00:06:31,230 --> 00:06:35,130
So let's begin with the
first part of the lecture.

115
00:06:35,130 --> 00:06:40,200
We will explore how to transform
real-world data to identify

116
00:06:40,200 --> 00:06:42,640
patients who do not
need treatment--

117
00:06:42,640 --> 00:06:46,940
those with good prognoses
who do well regardless.